## Summary

| Item | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Root cause** | `orders` table (500M rows) had only a PK index on `id` — no index on `user_id`, causing full sequential scans on every user-based query |
| **Fix applied** | `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_user_id ON orders(user_id)` |
| **Lock type** | `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking) — all INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE operations continued normally |
| **Build time** | ~180 seconds |
| **Residual locks** | None — clean completion |
| **Write impact** | Zero blocking — production writes were unaffected throughout |

The index was created safely using `CONCURRENTLY`, which avoids the `AccessExclusiveLock` that a standard `CREATE INDEX` would acquire. This means the 24/7 write traffic on the orders table was never interrupted. Query response times for user-based lookups should drop from 10+ seconds to milliseconds.
